    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>October 23 1880</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your courteous letter of Oct. 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I have no difficulty in answering your questions; but I cannot see how my answers can be of interest to anyone.—</p> 
    <p>I was born on Feb. 12<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1809.— On my return home after the voyage of the Beagle, I opened my first note-book for facts bearing on the origin of species in July 1837.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> In June 1842 I wrote a brief sketch of the notions then arrived at; &amp; this was enlarged in 1844 into a sketch of 230 M.S. pages.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> The Origin of Species was published near the close of 1859.—</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">No letter to CD dated 8 October 1880 to which this might be a reply has been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s ‘Notebook B’ is DAR 121; for a transcription, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5912.xml"><hi rend="italic">Notebooks</hi></ref>, pp. 167–236.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">There are various rough drafts and fair copies of CD’s species sketches of 1842 and 1844 (see DAR 6: 1–14, 16–50 for the 1842 sketch and DAR 7 and DAR 113 for versions of the 1844 essay).</note>
        </div>  
      
